  "body": "Output of `helm version`:\r\n(None, that's the error. Issue observed in `v3.0.0-rc.1` and master.)\r\n\r\nOutput of `kubectl version`:\r\n```\r\nClient Version: version.Info{Major:\"1\", Minor:\"12\", GitVersion:\"v1.12.0\", GitCommit:\"0ed33881dc4355495f623c6f22e7dd0b7632b7c0\", GitTreeState:\"clean\", BuildDate:\"2018-09-28T15:18:13Z\", GoVersion:\"go1.11\", Compiler:\"gc\", Platform:\"darwin/amd64\"}\r\nUnable to connect to the server: dial tcp 54.164.44.248:6443: i/o timeout\r\n```\r\n\r\nAn error in the kubeconfig causes helm invocations to exit with code 1 for all commands, and no output is observed. \r\n\r\nRunning with `HELM_DEBUG=true` emits the following:\r\n```\r\nhelm.go:71: [debug] invalid configuration: [client-key-data or client-key must be specified for admin to use the clientCert authentication method., certificate-authority-data and certificate-authority are both specified for test-clester. certificate-authority-data will override.]\r\n```\r\nThis line is actually helpful, but the error causes helm to exit, so it ought to be emitted at FATAL, not DEBUG. \r\n\r\nSeparately, I propose that a broken kubeconfig should not result in a fatal error for most helm subcommands like `--help` and `version`.",
